Spam Detect with NLP and Random Forest¶

This model accomplishes the task of checking for the presence of spam in the text. We use this model to evaluate the content of web pages such as titles and descriptions to help users complete the initial screening.

The dataset uses SMS Spam Collection Dataset on Kaggle and the model is a random forest. Our objective is to design a model to predict whether a message is from a human or is a spam

Import & Understand data¶

The SMS Spam Collection is a set of SMS tagged messages that have been collected for SMS Spam research. It contains one set of SMS messages in English of 5,574 messages, tagged acording being ham (legitimate) or spam.

Although it is not designed specifically for web content, it is reasonable for us to use it as a data sample, considering the generality of the language expression.

  • Messages labelled as Ham - are from a normal human being
  • Messages labelled as Spam - are marketing messages

Clean Data¶

  • Python needs to understand what are these words
  • We will let go of punctuations
  • Get rid of stop words
  • Break every sentence
In [35]:
Copied! 
import string
import nltk
import re

nltk.download('stopwords')
ps = nltk.PorterStemmer()
stopwords= nltk.corpus.stopwords.words('english')

def clean_text(text):
    remove_punct = "".join([word.lower() for word in text if word not in string.punctuation])
    tokens = re.split('\W+',remove_punct)
    noStop = ([ps.stem(word) for word in tokens if word not in stopwords])
    return noStop

clean_text("U dun say so early hor... U c already then say...")

def punct_percent(text):
    count = sum([1 for char in text if char in string.punctuation])
    return round(count/ (len(text) - text.count(" ")),3)*100

def website(text):
    if (len(re.findall('www|http|com|\.co',text))>0):
        return 1
    else:
        return 0


data['length'] = data['text'].apply(lambda x: len(x) - x.count(" "))
data['punct'] = data['text'].apply(lambda x : punct_percent(x))
data['long_number'] = data['text'].apply(lambda x : len(re.findall('\d{7,}',x)))
data['short_number'] = data['text'].apply(lambda x : len(re.findall('\d{4,6}',x)))
data['website'] = data['text'].apply(lambda x : website(x))

# Tweaking hyperparameters using Grid Search

def train_rf(n_est, depth):
    rf = RandomForestClassifier(n_estimators= n_est, max_depth= depth, n_jobs = -1)
    rf_model = rf.fit(x_train.values,y_train.values)
    y_pred=rf_model.predict(x_test.values)
    precision,recall,fscore,support =score(y_test,y_pred,pos_label='spam', average ='binary')
    print('Est: {} / Depth: {} / Precision : {} / Recall : {} / fscore : {} / Accuracy: {}'.format(n_est, depth, round(precision,3),round(recall,3),round(fscore,3),round((y_pred==y_test).sum()/len(y_test),3)))
    
for n_est in [10,30,50,70]:
    for depth in [20,40,60,80, None]:
        train_rf(n_est,depth)

PDP¶

Partial dependence plots (PDP) is a useful tool for gaining insights into the relationship between features and predictions. It helps us understand how different values of a particular feature impact model’s predictions. In this post, we will learn the very basics of PDPs and familiarise with a few useful ways to plot them using Scikit-learn.

                                PartialDependenceDisplay)

def pdp(var): 
    PartialDependenceDisplay.from_estimator(rf, x_train, [var], kind='both', centered=True);
